  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Strengthening the Local Production of Essential Medicines in Developing Countries through Advisory &amp; Capacity-Building Support - Phase 5</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Related to 120117 - Phase 5 - This project will continue UNIDO work rendered in support of the local production of essential generic medicines in developing and least developed countries (DCs/LDCs) that began with funding from Germany in January 2006. With phase 4 of the global project foreseen for conclusion at end-2013, the present proposal has been prepared against the background of a pledge from Germany of renewed funding, for
consolidating and enhancing the organization&#x2019;s work in the area of local pharmaceutical production (LPP) in 2014 and 2015. Substantively, the project will build on the progress and results of the past, notably the milestone achievement in phase 3 &amp; 4 following UNIDO&#x2019;s entering into a partnership with the African Union
Commission (AUC) in July 2011. The partnership culminated in the joint preparation and formal adoption at highest AU policy levels (AU Conference of Ministers of Health, AU Heads of State and Government Summit) of a &#x201C;Business Plan&#x201D; (BP) for the accelerated implementation of the 2007 AU Pharmaceutical Manufacturing Plan for Africa (PMPA) in mid-2012. Owned by the AU, the PMPA BP has become the main
reference document for action in support of LPP in Africa in the years ahead. UNIDO is the AUC&#x2019;s lead partner in the implementation of the PMPA BP and has been driving the early work towards the formation of a nucleus of partners. These partners (among others: WHO, UNAIDS and African Development Bank) have begun collaborating on early implementation of the Business Plan in Ghana, using the national
strategy developed by UNIDO in previous phases of the project as the template. Therefore, in addition to the continuation, deepening and roll-out of established UNIDO interventions, the present proposal will provide seed funding that enables UNIDO to continue to lead the start-up phase of the BP&#x2019;s implementation in collaboration with the AUC.
Advisory and capacity-building interventions will be geared to improving the operating environment of pharmaceutical manufacturers and thus address key constraints at policy and institutional levels.
Specifically, the main planned activity clusters comprise the following:
o Continue to support the implementation of select dimensions of the pharmaceutical manufacturing sector strategies that were developed and agreed by national stakeholders in earlier project phases in Kenya;
o Escort sector strategy development processes for the pharmaceutical industry in an additional country.
o Further strengthen the Southern African Generics Medicines Association (SAGMA) on its way to self-sufficiency and similar bodies in other sub-regions; support the newly founded pan-African apex body (Federation of African Pharmaceutical Manufacturers Associations/FAPMA) during startup and scale up;
o Continue and expand the support to St Luke Foundation (UR Tanzania) in delivering modular training courses on industrial pharmacy and an expansion of their offer;
o Apply the GMP Roadmap (combined with an EML risk assessment) as central tool (solution package) that has been designed to support further pharma sector development interventions, both within PMPA BP implementation and without;
o Work with the University of St. Gallen to tailor their programme on operational excellence in pharmaceutical manufacturing (OPEX) to the specific contexts of different African countries to support the development of a sustainable industry;
o Support the early PMPA BP implementation in three ways: (i) Coordinate on-going negotiations to establish the institutional/ management structure (including consortium of core partners, e.g. UNIDO, ADB, WHO, UNAIDS, USP and others); (ii) Engage in resource mobilisation to ensure broader and longer-term implementation assistance; and (iii) Collaborate with the nucleus of partners in early implementation of the Business Plan in Ghana.
Africa will remain the main regional focus for the project given that this is where the access to drugs crisis is most profound, where there is substantial political interest in the area, and where the previous projects have gained the most experience.</narrative>
  </description>
